{"author":"Joe Oakhart","author_email":"joeoakhart+bot@navapbc.com","author_id":"594c-9dcf-5ad6-4e6d","data":{"alias":"witching-subjective-skylark","description":"# S6 — Pluggable custom verifier\n\n## Why\nNo fixed set of verifiers can cover every organization's identity system (bespoke internal token\nservices, non-standard introspection like GitHub's, mTLS-header trust). A pluggable seam keeps\nthe capability open-ended — an operator drops in their own verifier without patching rebar — which\nis core to the \"generic, wide variety of environments\" goal.\n\n## What\nAdd a **custom-verifier** mode to `src/rebar/_mcp_auth.py`, selected via `mcp.auth.strategies`\nwith a param naming an import path (`module:factory`) resolving to an object implementing the\nofficial SDK `TokenVerifier` protocol. The factory returns a verifier the composite then treats\nlike any built-in. Loading validates that the resolved object satisfies the protocol and fails\nfast with a clear error otherwise.\n\n## Approach & rationale\nExpose the *same* `mcp.server.auth.provider.TokenVerifier` seam the built-ins use, loaded via a\nconfig-named import path (the established Python entry-point/import-string convention, e.g. how\nStarlette/uvicorn resolve app factories). This keeps custom verifiers ecosystem-compatible (any\nverifier written against the SDK protocol works) and adds no new abstraction — it reuses the seam\nthat already exists.\n\n## Scope\nThe custom-verifier loader + protocol validation only, on the S2 seam. Subset of the epic. Depends\non S2. Independent of S3/S4/S5.\n\n## Security\nBoundary-crossing and it loads operator-configured code. Requirements: the import path is an\n**operator-supplied trusted config value** (documented as such — never derived from a request or\nan untrusted source); resolution failure or a non-conforming object **fails closed** (server\nrefuses to start rather than silently running with no/So-partial auth); the loaded verifier is\nstill subject to the composite's mandatory audience/fail-closed contract.\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n- [ ] Unit test (tier: unit) asserts a valid `module:factory` config resolves to a working\n      verifier whose `verify_token` result is honored by the composite (observable oracle: a token\n      the custom verifier accepts → an `AccessToken`).\n- [ ] Unit test asserts an unresolvable import path, or a resolved object that does not implement\n      `verify_token`, causes a fail-closed startup error (observable oracle: startup raises with a\n      clear message) — negative controls for both cases.\n- [ ] Unit test asserts a custom verifier that returns an `AccessToken` with a wrong audience is\n      still rejected by the composite's mandatory audience check (the custom seam cannot bypass the\n      audience contract).\n- [ ] `docs/mcp-auth.md` (in S7) documents that the import path is a trusted operator config value.\n- [ ] `make lint && make typecheck && make test` pass.\n\n## Compatibility\nAdditive, opt-in via `mcp.auth.strategies`. No change to other verifiers or stdio.","id":"f978-847d-f874-4f2d","parent_id":"3393-83ca-5501-4e6e","priority":2,"tags":["mcp","auth","security"],"ticket_type":"story","title":"S6 — Pluggable custom verifier"},"env_id":"ade0f2ef-51cc-45a2-bb97-c09846cd3df5","event_type":"CREATE","timestamp":1784060331152364001,"uuid":"d3b9e7d6-b09c-4263-a639-af16652d856a"}